  "prompt": "What are some AngularJS interview questions?",
  "response": "Here are some common AngularJS interview questions, along with brief explanations or answers that you can expand on based on your experience and understanding:\n\n### Fundamental Concepts\n1. **What is AngularJS?**\n   - AngularJS is a JavaScript framework developed by Google that is used for building single-page applications (SPAs) with a focus on the MVC (Model-View-Controller) architecture.\n\n2. **What are the key features of AngularJS?**\n   - Two-way data binding, dependency injection, directives, templates, routing, and testing support.\n\n3. **What is MVC architecture in AngularJS?**\n   - MVC stands for Model-View-Controller, which separates an application into three interconnected components. The Model represents data, the View displays data, and the Controller handles user input.\n\n### Directives and Components\n4. **What are AngularJS directives?**\n   - Directives are special tokens in a markup that tell the library to do something to a DOM element. Common directives include `ng-model`, `ng-repeat`, and `ng-if`.\n\n5. **What is the difference between directives and components?**\n   - Directives are used to extend HTML with new attributes or elements, while components are a special type of directive that use a simpler API and are designed for creating reusable UI elements.\n\n### Data Binding & Scope\n6. **Explain two-way data binding.**\n   - Two-way data binding allows for automatic synchronization of data between the model and the view. If the model changes, the view reflects the change, and if the view changes (e.g., user input), the model updates accordingly.\n\n7. **What is scope in AngularJS?**\n   - Scope is an object that refers to the application model. It acts as a bridge between the controller and the view and allows data to flow between them.\n\n### Dependency Injection\n8. **What is dependency injection in AngularJS?**\n   - Dependency injection is a design pattern used to create and manage dependencies of classes/services for easier testing and maintenance. AngularJS provides a built-in dependency injection mechanism.\n\n9. **What are services in AngularJS?**\n   - Services are singleton objects that hold specific business logic or functionality and can be injected into controllers, directives, or other services to promote code reusability.\n\n### Routing and State Management\n10. **What is AngularJS routing?**\n    - AngularJS routing allows the application to navigate between different views or pages without refreshing the entire page. This is usually achieved using the `$routeProvider` and the `ngRoute` module.\n\n11. **How do you manage state in AngularJS applications?**\n    - State can be managed using services or factories that hold shared data throughout different components of the application, or by utilizing libraries like `ui-router`.\n\n### Performance and Optimization\n12. **How do you optimize AngularJS applications?**\n    - Techniques include using one-time bindings, limiting the number of watchers, using track by with ng-repeat, minimizing DOM manipulations, and breaking down large applications into smaller modules.\n\n### Testing\n13. **How can you test AngularJS applications?**\n    - AngularJS provides tools like Jasmine for unit testing controllers and services and Karma for running tests. End-to-end testing can be done using Protractor.\n\n14. **What are the benefits of using `$http` service?**\n    - The `$http` service simplifies making AJAX requests, handling responses and errors, and it returns promises for better handling of asynchronous operations.\n\n### Advanced Topics\n15. **What is a promise in AngularJS?**\n    - A promise is an object that represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value. AngularJS has built-in support for promises through the `$q` service.\n\n16. **Explain the digest cycle in AngularJS.**\n    - The digest cycle is the process by which AngularJS checks for changes in the models. It involves comparing the current state of model values to their previous state to determine if any updates are necessary.\n\nThese questions can help guide your preparation for an AngularJS interview, but remember to delve deeper into each topic based on your level of expertise and practical experience.",
